<i>tested on kernel version 5.14.21-gentoo</i>

<h4 id="introduction">introduction [<a href="#introduction">#</a>]</h4>
<p>
    for those who are new to configuring their own linux kernel,
    the process may seem daunting at first, but there isn't really
    much to worry about. it's a good idea to have a recovery cd
    just in case your kernel doesn't boot. i'll do my best to cover
    each section of the kernel configuration menu.
</p>

<h4 id="getting_into_the_menu">getting into the menu [<a href="#getting_into_the_menu">#</a>]</h4>
<p>
    go into your kernel source directory (typically <code>/usr/src/linux</code>),
    and run <code>make menuconfig</code>.
</p>

<h4 id="top_level_options">top level options [<a href="#top_level_options">#</a>]</h4>
<p>
    if using a 64 bit machine, enable a 64 bit kernel. if using kvm or
    virtual machines, enable virtualization. it's a good idea to enable
    loadable module support unless you know you don't need it, and the
    same goes for networking support (unless you're not using networking).
</p>

<h4 id="general_setup">general setup [<a href="#general_setup">#</a>]</h4>
<p>
    some things to consider enabling here are
    support for namespaces (<code>general setup -&gt; namespaces support -&gt; user namespace</code>)
    which is required by a lot of software (chromium and any apps based on it are a common example).
    this also helps with some steam games.

</p>
<p>
    if using an initramfs, enable support (<code>general setup -&gt; initial ram filesystem and ram disk</code>).
    if you're building a kernel for the first time and aren't sure, it's a good idea to build an initramfs. if
    the kernel boots with it, you can try removing it and seeing if it works without it. personally i don't need
    an initramfs.
</p>
<p>
    most other things are self explanatory, and for things that aren't you can use the help button.
    most of the help will tell you what to do if not sure about an option.
</p>

